{
  "texts": [
    "The active circles together with the ranks of the corresponding graded pieces of V 0 are called the irregular class Θ of (E, ∇).",
    "-The formal local system V 0 can equivalently be thought of as a local system on the topological space I supported on its active circles (see Theorem 2.4).",
    "-The irregular class determines an auxiliary surface Σ(Θ) (obtained from Σ by puncturing at some points), a fission surface Σ(Θ) (see Remark 3.6) and a finite collection of distinguished paths γ i→j in the fission surface, the so-called Stokes paths, whose endpoints i, j are points on some active circles of Θ (see Remark 4.10).",
    "• The full Stokes data of (E, ∇) are encoded in terms of a Stokes local system V, which is a local system (of finite-dimensional vector spaces) on Σ(Θ) satisfying certain conditions (see §3.2).",
    "-The Stokes local system V of (E, ∇) determines in particular the associated formal local system V 0, which lives on the boundary circle ∂ ⊂ Σ(Θ)."
  ]
}